    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>EXPANSION BY BILLITON</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Suzanne Kapner</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Kapner, Suzanne</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Britain's Billiton PLC wins battle for Canadian mining concern Rio Algom Ltd, after Noranda Inc, rival Canadian concern that owns 5.4 million shares of Rio Algon, abandons competing offer; deal values Rio Algom at about $1.13 billion; Billiton joins Anglo American PLC and Glencore International AG in consortium that bought Colombian government's 50 percent stake in Cerrejon Zona Norte coal mine for $384 million; consortium will form joint venture with Intercore, subsidiary of Exxon Mobil Corp, to manage the mine (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The British mining and metals company, Billiton P.L.C. said it won the battle for the Canadian mining concern Rio Algom Ltd., after Noranda Inc., a rival Canadian concern that owns 5.4 million shares of Rio Algom, abandoned a competing offer. The deal values Rio Algom at about $1.13 billion, or $27 a share. At the same time, Billiton joined Anglo American P.L.C. and Glencore International A.G. in a consortium that bought the Columbian government's 50 percent stake in the Cerrejon Zona Norte coal mine for $384 million. The consortium will now form a joint venture with Intercore, a subsidiary of the Exxon Mobil Corporation, to manage the mine.</p>
        <p>Suzanne Kapner</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>The British mining and metals company, Billiton P.L.C. said it won the battle for the Canadian mining concern Rio Algom Ltd., after Noranda Inc., a rival Canadian concern that owns 5.4 million shares of Rio Algom, abandoned a competing offer. The deal values Rio Algom at about $1.13 billion, or $27 a share. At the same time, Billiton joined Anglo American P.L.C. and Glencore International A.G. in a consortium that bought the Columbian government's 50 percent stake in the Cerrejon Zona Norte coal mine for $384 million. The consortium will now form a joint venture with Intercore, a subsidiary of the Exxon Mobil Corporation, to manage the mine.</p>
